04037nam a22005775i 9780774838948DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748389487 a10.59962/97807748389482doi  a(DE-B1597)662270  a(OCoLC)1101625209  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJL193b.B47 2019 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a324.9712231 aBesco, Randy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIdentities and Interests :bRace, Ethnicity, and Affinity Voting /cRandy Besco. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b29 tables, 19 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tFraming and Explaining Affinity Voting -- tCoethnic and Racialized Affinity in Canada -- tThe Importance of Self-Identification -- tEthnic Identity and Voter Behaviour -- tThe Role of Interests, Ideology, and Policy -- tAffinity Voting in Federal Elections -- tConclusion -- tAppendices -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe electoral behaviour of racialized voters and politicians has captured little attention outside the United States. Identities and Interests offers a new perspective on the role of racial and ethnic identities in Canadian elections. Combining survey data experiments with candidate and census data, Randy Besco demonstrates that self-identification matters far more than self-interest, ideology, or policy. The largest minority groups – Chinese and South Asian Canadians – tend to support candidates of their own ethnicity. Yet inter-minority affinity voting also reveals the potential for “rainbow coalitions” and how minorities themselves think in terms of a white/non-white divide. Besco distinguishes pure in-group bias from the positive effects stemming from affinity voting and calls for a more nuanced evaluation of the role of identity in politics. Overall, his findings have major implications for social movements, issue opinions, fundraising, and political leadership races. Identities and Interests gets to the heart of our understanding of democracy and citizenship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aMinoritiesxPolitical activityzCanada. 0aRacexPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aVotingzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311141772140uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483894840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774838948423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774838948/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-141772-1  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles